			<h4><a id="comment_link_64338321" name="comment_link_64338321" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23266759&amp;cid=64338321" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64338321)" >TFA handwaves away the false positive rate</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64338321" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64338321); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~GrumpySteen">GrumpySteen</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~GrumpySteen">( 1250194 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64338321">		
		on Saturday March 23, 2024 @05:01AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23266759&amp;cid=64338321">#64338321</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64338321"><p>It's easy to catch more cancers than doctors do if you crank up the settings and flag everything that even remotely looks like cancer.</p><p>I found what appears to be <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10245180/" title="nih.gov">the study</a> [nih.gov] and Mia flagged 13.0% of the scans vs a human flagging just 5.4%.  That's a lot of false positives that had to be examined by humans to find 11 real positives.</p><p>Mia might be a useful tool someday, but the press on this is putting way too positive a spin on the results.</p></div>
	</div>

